{"kind":"article","primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"text":"Overview","level":2,"type":"heading","anchor":"overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To achieve this, you can include the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":".tool"},{"text":" parameter to the ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Godot","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"like this:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["@Godot(.tool)","class Line3D: MeshInstance3D {","","    \/\/ This will be called in the editor","    override func _ready() {","\t\/\/ Run some code here","    }","","    \/\/ And so will this one","    override func _process(delta _: Double) {","\t\/\/ Check if we are running in the editor, or in the game","        if Engine.isEditorHint() {","            doEditorWork ()","        } else {","\t    doGameWork ()","\t}","    }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can use it for doing many things, but it is mostly useful in level design"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for visually presenting things that are hard to predict ourselves. Here are some"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"use cases:"}]},{"items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you have a cannon that shoots cannonballs affected by physics (gravity),"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"you  can draw the cannonball’s trajectory in the editor, making level design a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"lot easier.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you have jumppads with varying jump heights, you can draw the maximum jump"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"height a player would reach if it jumped on one, also making level design","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"easier."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If your player doesn’t use a sprite, but draws itself using code, you can"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"make that drawing code execute in the editor to see your player.","type":"text"}]}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"style":"warning","name":"Warning","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":""},{"type":"codeVoice","code":".tool"},{"type":"text","text":" extensions run inside the editor, and let you access the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"scene tree of the currently edited scene. This is a powerful feature which","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"also comes with caveats, as the editor does not include protections for"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"potential misuse of ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Godot(.tool)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" scripts. Be extremely cautious when","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"manipulating the scene tree, especially via ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Node\/queueFree"},{"text":", as it can","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"cause crashes if you free a node while the editor runs logic involving it."}]}],"type":"aside"},{"text":"Detecting the Editor","anchor":"Detecting-the-Editor","type":"heading","level":1},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In your code, you can call the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Engine\/isEditorHint()","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" to determine whether"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the code is running inside the editor or in the game, and adjust your various","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"methods accordingly."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"title":"Running Code in the Godot Editor","role":"article"},"abstract":[{"text":"There are cases where you might want some of your Swift code for your extension","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to run while it is being used in the Godot Editor.","type":"text"}],"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"minor":3,"major":0},"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"seeAlsoSections":[{"generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/CustomTypes","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes"],"title":"Articles and Tutorials"}],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/runningineditor"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"sections":[],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"references":{"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Exports":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/exports","title":"Exports","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","kind":"article","abstract":[{"text":"In Godot, class members can be exported. This means their value gets saved along","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"with the resource (such as the scene) they’re attached to. They will also be","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"available for editing in the property editor. Exporting is done by using the"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Signals":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/signals","title":"Signals","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals in Godot are used by objects to post interesting events that are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"taking place, and can be used by users to easily add behavior and react","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to changes.","type":"text"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Differences":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/differences","title":"SwiftGodot API differences to GDScript","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This document lists some common differences between GDSscript and SwiftGodot."}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/CustomTypes":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/customtypes","title":"Using Custom Types","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/CustomTypes","kind":"article","abstract":[{"text":"You will typically extend the functionality of your Godot game by creating","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"classes that derive from one of the various Godot types and adjust the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"behavior accordingly."}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variants":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variants","title":"Variants","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","kind":"article","abstract":[{"text":"Follow up on the fundamental building block of Godot’s data types.","type":"text"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Engine/isEditorHint()":{"fragments":[{"text":"static","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"func","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"isEditorHint","kind":"identifier"},{"text":"() -> ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Bool","preciseIdentifier":"s:Sb","kind":"typeIdentifier"}],"type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Returns "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"true"},{"type":"text","text":" if the script is currently running inside the editor, "},{"code":"false","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" otherwise. This is useful for "},{"code":"@tool","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" scripts to conditionally draw editor helpers, or prevent accidentally running “game” code that would affect the scene state while in the editor:"}],"title":"isEditorHint()","kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/engine\/iseditorhint()","role":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Engine\/isEditorHint()"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/BindingNodes":{"kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/bindingnodes","title":"Referencing Nodes from your Scene","abstract":[{"text":"You will find yourself referencing nodes from a scene in your code.   In","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"GDScript, that is usually achieved by using the dollar sign and the name of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"object you want to reference.","type":"text"}],"role":"article","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot":{"title":"SwiftGodot","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot","role":"collection","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot","abstract":[{"text":"Framework to write Godot Game Extensions using the Swift Programming Language.","type":"text"}],"kind":"symbol","type":"topic"}}}